ce:section.ce:para:
Organic supercapacitors have dominated the market of high-power electrochemical energy storage supplies owing to the merits of fast charge–discharge rate, high-working voltage window, long cycle life, and high safety [1–3]. Porous carbon is the key electrode material for organic supercapacitors thanks to its large surface area, good physicochemical stability, moderate electric conductivity, and low cost [4,5]. With the growing demand for miniaturization and lightweight in devices, improving the volumetric capacitance (Cv
                     ) of porous carbon is a major objective because it governs the energy and power performance of the devices working in limited space [6,7]. Generally, the ions in organic electrolytes have relatively large sizes, and their storage mainly relies on the electrical double-layer mechanism [8,9]. Therefore, abundant large-micropores and high specific surface area are the basic demand for porous carbons to adequately accommodate organic ions. Sufficient transport channels are also highly required to ensure fast ion storage kinetics and high-rate performance [10]. However, such required structure usually leads to a low compaction density (ρ, 0.4–0.6 g cm−3) [11,12]. Furthermore, a lot of micropores are hard to be utilized because of a) the mismatching between the small-sized pores and the large-sized organic ions and b) poor ion migration kinetics in small and tortuous pores, resulting in a limited gravimetric capacitance (Cg
                     ). According to the equation: Cv
                      = Cg
                      × ρ, it can be clearly see why the volumetric performance of porous carbon is limited (50–70 F cm−3), and hard to be improved in organic electrolytes [13,14].
